<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-P1u99XGbuR1ZKFUIEPMjEA" name="user-experience_navigation_map,9.453117380007355E-306" guid="-P1u99XGbuR1ZKFUIEPMjEA" changeDate="2005-11-21T08:40:27.016-0800" version="7.1.0">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The User-Experience Navigation Map is represented in a UML class diagram containing the User-Experience Elements and&#xD;
    the key navigation paths between them.&amp;nbsp; These associations don't represent every possible path, just the ones&#xD;
    captured in the Storyboards' flows of events. This distinction is important because the User-Experience Model needs to&#xD;
    remain detached from the details of the software architecture as much as possible, since the intent is not to present&#xD;
    just another view of the detailed Design Model. For information on how to model the User-Experience Elements, see &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../extend.ux_model/guidances/guidelines/user_experience_element_F0023A91.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;9.763858677053972E-306&quot;>Guideline: User-Experience Element&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    There is one User-Experience Navigation Map per &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../extend.ux_model/workproducts/user_experience_model_E11A34D3.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{34EE80D4-460E-494D-BC01-E34D5CB7756A}&quot;>User-Experience Model&lt;/a> (the navigation map is essentially a&#xD;
    combination of all of the &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../extend.ux_model/guidances/guidelines/user_experience_storyboard_CCF3852D.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;1.795569619094057E-305&quot;>User-Experience Storyboard&lt;/a> participant diagrams). If the total number of&#xD;
    User-Experience Elements is small enough to permit them to realistically appear in a single diagram (say, less than 30&#xD;
    elements), then one diagram can be used. If there are too many User-Experience Elements, then the User-Experience&#xD;
    Navigation Map should be expressed as a series of diagrams, with each diagram focusing on a related set of information.&#xD;
    Some possibilities for separate User-Experience Navigation Map diagrams include:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;p>&#xD;
            Actor-focused class diagrams.&amp;nbsp; Each would contain the User-Experience Elements that a particular actor&#xD;
            might view.&#xD;
        &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;p>&#xD;
            Function-focused class diagrams. Each would contain the User-Experience Elements that are accessed when&#xD;
            performing a particular set of application functions (like account maintenance).&lt;br />&#xD;
             Note: It may be tempting to create Use-Case-focused diagrams.&amp;nbsp; However, such diagrams would be redundant&#xD;
            with the User-Experience Storyboard participant diagrams.&#xD;
        &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;p>&#xD;
            Architecturally significant User-Experience Elements.&amp;nbsp; The most important User-Experience Elements and&#xD;
            their navigation paths. Diagrams of this type can function as a summary of the User-Experience Model, and can&#xD;
            be of great help in, for example, a review of the model, or in a prioritization of which parts of the model&#xD;
            will be focused upon in the current iteration.&#xD;
        &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    To reduce clutter on the User-Experience Navigation Map diagrams, just include the User-Experience Elements, their&#xD;
    names, and their navigation associations.&amp;nbsp; Do not include the User-Experience Elements dynamic content&#xD;
    (attributes) or actions (operations).&amp;nbsp; That level of detail is reserved for the Participant diagrams defined&#xD;
    within the User-Experience Storyboards, where the scope of the diagram is a little more manageable (i.e., a single Use&#xD;
    Case as opposed to an entire application).&amp;nbsp; The User-Experience Navigation Map is meant to be a summation of these&#xD;
    individual diagrams and provide a &quot;big picture&quot; of the structure of the User-Experience Model.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The decision to what level of detail is appropriate for User-Experience Navigation Map diagrams will depend upon the&#xD;
    individual teams building the model. Your project may want to define exactly what should be developed by your teams.&#xD;
    These guidelines are meant to provide a starting point for a development team to tailor their own guidelines.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    Once decided upon, the guidelines for the project should be captured in the project-specific guidelines.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    For more information on identifying and modeling navigation for User-Experience Elements, see &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../extend.ux_model/guidances/guidelines/user_experience_element_F0023A91.html#Navigation&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;9.763858677053972E-306&quot;>Guideline: User-Experience Element, Navigation&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br /></mainDescription>
